<p><b>Ray Douglas Bradbury</b> (born August 22, 1920) is an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> <a href="/wiki/Literature" title="Literature">mainstream</a>, <a href="/wiki/Fantasy" title="Fantasy">fantasy</a>, <a href="/wiki/Horror_fiction" title="Horror fiction">horror</a>, <a href="/wiki/Science_fiction" title="Science fiction">science fiction</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Mystery_(fiction)" title="Mystery (fiction)">mystery</a> <a href="/wiki/Writer" title="Writer">writer</a>.</p>
<p>Best known for his <a href="/wiki/Dystopia" title="Dystopia">dystopian</a> novel <i><a href="/wiki/Fahrenheit_451" title="Fahrenheit 451">Fahrenheit 451</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/The_Martian_Chronicles" title="The Martian Chronicles">The Martian Chronicles</a></i>, Bradbury is widely considered one of the greatest and most popular American writers of <a href="/wiki/Speculative_fiction" title="Speculative fiction">speculative fiction</a> of the twentieth century.</p>
<p>Ray Bradbury's popularity has been increased by more than 20 television shows and films using his writings (see <i><a href="#Adaptations" title="">Adaptations of his work</a></i>).</p>
